<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2>Wisconsin's bar refrigeration specialist, in service across Southern California</h2>
    <p>
      Perlick is the heritage name in bar refrigeration. The company has been a Milwaukee family business since 1917 — independently
      owned, not consolidated into one of the foodservice equipment conglomerates — and the brand built its reputation around the bar:
      back-bar coolers, bottle coolers, glass chillers, draft beer systems, and the heavy-duty under-counter refrigeration that anchors
      a serious cocktail program. The commercial reach-in line came later, but it carries the same construction discipline as the bar
      heritage — heavier-gauge stainless than mid-tier reach-ins, premium gasket compounds, commercial-grade compressors that earn
      their place over a long service life.
    </p>
    <p>
      This page covers Perlick <em>commercial refrigeration for cold storage</em> — Signature Series HC and HP reach-ins, Sottile
      narrow 18" undercounter, ADA-compliant commercial models, pass-through units, bar back coolers used for bottle and ingredient
      storage, refrigerated commercial prep. If your Perlick is a draft beer system with tap towers, beer-line trunk cooling, glycol
      lines, or CO₂ regulation, the right page for you is
      <a href="/brands/perlick-draft-beer-system-repair/">/brands/perlick-draft-beer-system-repair/</a> — separate practice, separate
      parts inventory, separate technician specialty. Residential undercounter is at
      <a href="/brands/perlick-refrigerator-repair/">/brands/perlick-refrigerator-repair/</a>; outdoor at
      <a href="/brands/perlick-outdoor-refrigerator-repair/">/brands/perlick-outdoor-refrigerator-repair/</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 SERIES COVERAGE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02, Series and model coverage</p>
    <h2>What we service across the Perlick commercial lineup</h2>

    <h3>Signature Series HC and HP commercial reach-ins</h3>
    <p>
      Perlick's flagship commercial reach-in line. HC and HP variants cover one-, two-, and three-section configurations in refrigerator
      and freezer formats with solid or glass doors. Used heavily in restaurant back-of-house, hotel kitchens, hospital food service,
      and high-volume catering operations. Heavier stainless than mid-tier brands — both interior and exterior cabinet — and a higher-end
      gasket and door-hinge package designed for commercial cycle abuse. Common service items are gasket replacement after 3-5 years of
      heavy use, evaporator and condenser fan motor replacements at the 8-12 year mark, and the occasional defrost-system intervention
      on freezer variants. Compressor end-of-life typically runs 14-18 years with maintenance.
    </p>

    <h3>Sottile narrow 18" undercounter commercial</h3>
    <p>
      Perlick's purpose-built narrow chassis — fits installation contexts where standard 24" undercounter won't go. Common use is in
      tight bar back layouts, prep stations with limited width, and any retrofit where the existing cabinet opening predates standard
      commercial dimensions. Mechanically similar to the Signature Series at smaller scale; service approach is the same. Parts ship
      through Perlick authorized distribution rather than common-truck stock because Sottile-specific items don't see the volume of
      the standard width chassis.
    </p>

    <h3>ADA-compliant commercial units</h3>
    <p>
      ADA-height compliance for commercial environments — accessible-counter installations in healthcare, public service, and
      hospitality where ADA conformance is required. The chassis is engineered for the lower mounting height and accessible clearances
      while preserving the commercial-grade refrigeration mechanicals. Service approach is identical to standard commercial; the only
      practical difference for the technician is the counter height during access. We work on these regularly across LA's healthcare
      and hospitality footprint.
    </p>

    <h3>Pass-through bar refrigerators</h3>
    <p>
      Doors on both faces of the cabinet — kitchen-side loading, bar-side service. Common in restaurants where the bar program is
      stocked from a back-of-house cold storage area without the bar staff leaving station. Service includes the same items as the
      Signature Series plus extra attention to the dual-gasket configuration: pass-through units cycle two doors per unit, so gasket
      wear comes faster on whichever face sees more traffic. We replace both gaskets on the same call when one shows wear, because
      doing them separately costs more in the long run.
    </p>

    <h3>Bar back coolers — cold storage focus</h3>
    <p>
      Used for bottle storage, prepared ingredient holding, dairy and citrus inventory at the bar. Cold storage only — these are not
      the draft beer or tap units. The mechanicals are conventional commercial refrigeration; failures cluster around door cycling
      (gaskets, hinges, latches), condenser cleanliness in tight bar back layouts where ventilation is limited, and the drain line on
      under-counter units that run a long horizontal drain.
    </p>

    <h3>Refrigerated commercial prep</h3>
    <p>
      Sandwich and salad prep tables with overhead pan rails, chef bases under the cookline, undercounter refrigerated worktops.
      Heavy-cycle use through service. Common service items match other prep-table refrigeration: evaporator fan motor, drain-line
      clogging from food debris, gasket fatigue. Drain-line flushing as part of routine maintenance prevents the most common
      preventable failure mode (drain backup, water in cabinet, food contamination risk).
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 COMMON FAILURES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03, Common failure patterns</p>
    <h2>What we look at first on a Perlick commercial call</h2>
    <p>
      Diagnostic order on a Perlick commercial reach-in or bar back cooler that's not holding setpoint:
    </p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Condenser cleanliness — first stop, every time.</strong> Bar back environments and busy kitchens both put dust, lint,
        and airborne grease on the condenser coil at a rate that surprises operators. A coil clogged enough to choke compressor cooling
        is the cause of about a third of "not cooling" calls we run on Perlick commercial. Symptom is a unit running constantly with
        warm cabinet, often paired with a hot exterior near the compressor section. Diagnostic is a five-minute visual check; the fix
        is a deep clean and re-test, no parts.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Door gasket fatigue.</strong> Perlick gaskets are higher-end than mid-tier commercial, but they still wear under
        constant cycling. Three to five years on a heavily-cycled bar back or pass-through is typical service life for the gasket
        itself. Symptom is icing on the evaporator (moisture infiltration), visible compression set on the gasket lip, and a unit
        struggling to hold setpoint during peak service. Replacement gaskets are stocked for common configurations; sourcing for
        Sottile and ADA-specific models runs through Perlick authorized distribution.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Evaporator fan motor.</strong> The fan inside the cabinet runs whenever the compressor is calling for cooling. After
        eight to twelve years of duty, bearings or windings give. Symptom is a cabinet that cools the front half but lets the back warm
        up, or warm spots on the upper-rear shelves of a tall reach-in. Replacement is a 30-45 minute job once the part is on hand.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Defrost cycle on freezer variants.</strong> Perlick commercial freezers use modern electronic defrost control on
        current production. When the timer or thermostat fails, defrost either doesn't happen (evaporator ices over, cooling collapses)
        or defrosts too often (cabinet temperature swings, frozen product partially thaws and refreezes). Diagnostic isolates whether
        the timer, the thermostat, or the heating element is at fault; we don't guess on this one.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Compressor end-of-life.</strong> Year 14 to 18 on a well-maintained Signature Series with regular condenser cleaning
        and gasket replacement. Sooner if the unit ran in a hot bar back room without ventilation, or if a previous service shop
        substituted an aftermarket compressor at a prior repair. Compressor swap on a Perlick is meaningful labor and refrigerant work
        — $1,200-$2,200 typical range depending on configuration and access — and we lay out the math against replacement honestly.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Drain-line clogs on prep tables and chef bases.</strong> Food debris in the drain line is the single most common
        preventable failure on prep refrigeration. Symptom is water pooling in the cabinet, ice accumulation around the drain pan, or
        a faint sour smell during prep service. The fix is drain-line flushing and a re-evaluation of the kitchen's condensate
        management. Quarterly drain flushing on a maintenance contract eliminates this entirely.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 LA CONTEXT -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04, Where we work most on Perlick commercial</p>
    <h2>The LA Perlick footprint our techs know best</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Hollywood, West Hollywood, and Downtown LA cocktail bars.</strong> The serious bar program — high-end cocktail venues,
      hotel bars, the better lounges — runs Perlick because the brand is purpose-built for bar refrigeration's specific demands:
      door-cycle abuse, tight installation footprints, ingredient storage at very specific temperatures, ADA conformance in public-facing
      installs. We are the after-hours call for several of these venues when a back-bar cooler fails on a Friday afternoon and Saturday
      service is six hours away.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Hotel restaurants and rooftop bars.</strong> Beverly Hills, West Hollywood, Santa Monica, Pasadena hotels with serious
      F&B programs typically have Perlick equipment in the bar back, prep stations, and pass-through configurations between bar and
      kitchen. Hotel service runs more carefully than independent restaurant — facility engineering coordination, vendor onboarding
      with COI on file, scheduling around guest service hours.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Restaurants with serious bar programs.</strong> Beverly Hills, West Hollywood, Newport Beach, Pasadena, the Westside —
      restaurants where the bar contributes meaningful revenue use Perlick reach-ins and pass-through models for bar inventory and
      cocktail prep. Service typically runs between meal services or during the slow afternoon block when the kitchen and bar can both
      go down for two hours without losing the night.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Healthcare and ADA-compliant installations.</strong> Hospital cafés, clinical-adjacent food service, public-service
      facility kitchens. ADA-compliant Perlick units are the right answer in these contexts — service approach is the same as standard
      commercial, with extra attention to facility access protocols and any infection-control requirements at the building entry.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05, Recent repairs</p>
    <h2>What this month looked like on Perlick commercial</h2>
    <div class="repair-cards">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <p class="repair-quote">"Back-bar cooler at 50°F two hours before Friday service, and we open at 5."</p>
        <p>
          High-end cocktail bar in West Hollywood, Signature Series HC two-door undercounter, install year per the operator about 2019.
          Diagnostic ran condenser first — heavily fouled with airborne grease from the kitchen pass next door, and the bar back room
          was running 88°F with no exhaust. Deep-cleaned coil, verified refrigerant charge under EPA 608, ran cabinet pull-down for an
          hour while the staff prepped. Cabinet at 36°F by 4:30 PM. Recommended adding exhaust ventilation in the bar back room and
          quarterly preventative maintenance going forward.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <p class="repair-quote">"Pass-through has water on the floor every morning, kitchen-side door won't seal."</p>
        <p>
          Restaurant in Beverly Hills, Signature Series HP pass-through reach-in, install year per facility approximately 2017. Two
          gasket failures confirmed — the kitchen-side gasket compressed permanently and lost the bottom seal, which let warm humid
          kitchen air into the cabinet, condense, and drip overnight. Replaced both gaskets (kitchen side and bar side — it's the right
          time to do both at once), inspected hinges, verified door alignment. Drain-line flushed during the same call. Operator was
          surprised both gaskets weren't more obviously failed; the bar-side gasket was within months of the same compression-set
          failure.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <p class="repair-quote">"Sottile undercounter behind the host stand stopped cooling, can't reach the back."</p>
        <p>
          Boutique restaurant in Newport Beach, Sottile 18" narrow undercounter, install year per the operator approximately 2020.
          The unit was installed in a millwork pocket with ten inches of rear clearance — barely accessible. Diagnostic isolated to
          a failed evaporator fan motor; the part shipped from Perlick distribution overnight. Tech returned the next morning, pulled
          the unit forward enough to access the rear panel, replaced the motor, verified normal cooling and tightened the rear-panel
          gasket on reinstall (a common detail Perlick service requires that aftermarket techs sometimes miss). Three-hour total
          service window across two visits.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 WHY US -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">06, Why us, specifically</p>
    <h2>What makes us a fit for Perlick commercial work</h2>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>EPA 608 Universal certification (#1346255700410).</strong> Required by federal law for any work involving the refrigerants Perlick uses across its commercial lineup. We perform the refrigerant work legally and document the charge for compliance records.</li>
      <li><strong>BHGS Registration #A49573 and CSLB C-20 HVAC.</strong> California state coverage for commercial refrigeration work plus the HVAC scope that comes up on prep tables and chef bases tied into kitchen exhaust and gas systems.</li>
      <li><strong>Perlick OEM parts only.</strong> No aftermarket compressors, no aftermarket control boards, no substitutions that void manufacturer warranty or shorten the chassis life. We source through Perlick authorized distribution.</li>
      <li><strong>$120 commercial diagnostic, waived with repair.</strong> Transparent flat fee, no surprise drive-time charges within our five-county service area.</li>
      <li><strong>Coordinated service for venues with mixed Perlick equipment.</strong> If your venue has both commercial reach-ins (this page) and draft beer systems (the dedicated page), we coordinate visits so a single dispatch covers both refrigeration practices when possible.</li>
      <li><strong>BBB Accredited Business and $1M general liability insured.</strong> COI provided on request — required for most hotel and hospitality vendor onboarding.</li>
      <li><strong>After-hours and emergency dispatch.</strong> Phones answered 24/7. Bar refrigeration emergencies don't wait for business hours, and neither do we.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

